                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Sigh...I haven't had much time to post recently, but I really need to vent a bit.  I'm suffering terribly from the current fragmenting of the game scene.  My EQ guild (who I love) all moved to EQ2, my old RL friends all moved to WoW, and my husband and I love playing City of Heroes.  As a result, I now have 4 accounts (or will once I get back to the U.S. and buy WoW) with no time to play any of them.  The real frustration is coming from dealing with my RL friends, who have become WoW fanatics to a point I've never seen before.  I feel like I'm not allowed to talk about any other game in the world, in fact like I'm not allowed to talk about any other topic at all but WoW and how wonderful it is.  Last weekend they condescended to play an hour in CoH with us and it was really obvious they were like, "Why are you still playing this crappy game?"  I liked WoW fine when I tried it in beta, but I never got caught on fire like my friends did.  I really feel very guilty and down right now, like someone who went to a religious revival meeting and all her friends had a religious conversion and I'm stuck there kind of singing along and feeling like a schmuck for not being honestly rapturous.
<br />

<br />
See, now I've typed all that I'm kind of like, "What am I hoping to achieve by posting this here?"  If anyone responds at all the thread will probably turn into a shouting match about the relative merits of WoW, and I'm not interested in that.  I'm mostly just blowing off steam and wondering why it seems necessary to so many people to treat games like a religion sometimes--"Love my game or be cast into the seventh circle of hell reserved for heretics and the blasphemous!"  I suppose part of my unhappiness is my own "religious" tendencies, so when my friends say "Everquest?  Didn't we used to play some game called that before, when we weren't having fun?"  it smarts.  But I don't get angry when them about it or argue with them--there's no denying (I guess, I'm sure someone can) that EQ is no longer the cutting-edge game.  
<br />

<br />
It just makes me wistful that although I understand people leaving EQ (indeed, I haven't logged in for a month or two), I haven't been able to "give my heart" to another game in the same way.  Oh, I love CoH, but it's a casual, no-strings sort of love, and not the grand passion I had with EQ and my friends have with WoW.  Will I ever truly love again?
<br />

<br />
OK, over-inflated religious and love metaphors, check.  Whiny angst, check.  Discuss among yourselves as you see fit.  
<br />

<br />
 <img src="images/smiles/icon_razz.gif" alt="icon_razz.gif" border="0" /></span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><img src="http://home.att.ne.jp/apple/dmolden/screenshots/pixcol.gif" border="0" />
<br />
<a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=611032" target="_blank" class="postlink">Columbyne Celebfin</a></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
